    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the confusion! There was no typo, but I did slip up and use some goblin metaphors that weren't quite right for a real estate explanation. You are absolutely right to ask for clarity on the actual legal process.\n\nAn **escrow account** is a neutral, third-party account (usually held by a title company or an attorney) where the buyer's down payment and the seller's proceeds are kept separate until the closing conditions are met. It is designed to protect both parties by ensuring that funds are only released when all paperwork is signed, inspections are passed, and the deed is officially transferred.\n\nIn the context of your Toronto home purchase, the \"goblin\" in my previous analogy was simply the **Escrow Agent** or **Title Company**. They act as the impartial guardian of the funds, ensuring that the money doesn't get lost or misused before the final handshake.\n\nTo answer your question directly: You need an escrow account to prevent fraud and ensure a smooth closing. Without it, the buyer's money could be at risk if the seller backs out, or the seller's money could be at risk if the buyer fails to close. It is the standard safety protocol for every real estate transaction in",
